Note that these predictions of the model regarding the value of the gauge coupling $g_R$ and the mass of the extra gauge bosons, given in Eqs.~(\ref{coupling}) and~(\ref{Wpr}), do not coincide with the diboson resonance noticed in the $8$ TeV LHC data~\cite{exp,exp2,exp3,exp4,exp5,exp6,Brehmer:2015cia,Aydemir:2015nfa,Aydemir:2015oob,Evans:2015cqq,Brehmer:2015dan,Dev:2015pga}, which has not appeared so far in the $13$ TeV data according to the first results of the second run~\cite{atlasdba13,atlasdbb13,atlasdbc13}. These are our model's rather specific predictions. However, we note that the mass values of the new gauge bosons change significantly with the choice of the symmetry breaking scale $M_R$ in the TeV-scale. Therefore, these mass values are not very distinctive of the model. The more reliable and robust prediction is rather the values of the gauge couplings in the TeV-scale, given in Eq.~(\ref{coupling}), which do not change noticeable with the choice of the value of $M_R$ (in the TeV-scale) due to their logarithmic dependence on the energy scale.  

\newpage
\section{Summary}
\label{summary}

In this paper, we have proposed to explain the $750$ GeV diphoton excess, recently reported at the LHC~\cite{CMS,ATLAS}, by a SM-singlet scalar through its loop interaction with a color-triplet scalar in the non-supersymmetric $SO(10)$ grand unification framework. We have identifed the $750$ GeV scalar as the excitation of the SM-singlet component ($\Delta_{R_1}^{0}$) of the $SU(2)_R$-triplet-scalar, which is also responsible for the breaking of the gauge group of the left-right model, $SU(2)_L\otimes SU(2)_R\otimes U(1)_{B-L}\otimes SU(3)_C$, into that of the SM, by acquiring a VEV in the TeV-scale. The colored scalar we have considered is remnant from the breaking of the Pati-Salam gauge group, $SU(2)_L\otimes SU(2)_R\otimes SU(4)_C$, into that of the left-right model. Note that we have stayed in the minimal picture in terms of the total field content; the model does not have any extra matter fields or any $SO(10)$ multiplets in the scalar content other than the ones required to begin with. 

The colored scalars in our set-up effectively induce the necessary interaction terms that lead to two-photon final states after being produced via gluon fusion. We have found that there is a region of parameter space that can explain the desired
diphoton excess. Moreover, we have obtained the excluded regions for all the relevant 8 TeV data from the LHC. 
Although the cross section upper bound from the 8 TeV diphoton resonance data is comparable to that for the
13 TeV, there is still a small region of the favored parameter space that can account for the excess. 

The unifications of the couplings in the model are successfully realized, where the TeV-scale colored-triplet plays an important role. As discussed in~\cite{Aydemir:2015oob}, it is very difficult to achieve a successful $SO(10)$ grand unification set-up with a TeV-scale left-right model. Slightly modifying the low energy scalar content by allowing a number of colored scalars, originated from various Pati-Salam multiplets, to become light generates the possibility to accommodate a TeV-scale left-right model in the $SO(10)$ grand unification framework. Among a number of low energy scalar configurations, the ones with the very color-triplet selected in our model appear to particularly stand out~\cite{Aydemir:2015oob}. We also note that the values obtained for the intermediate scale (where the Pati-Salam is broken) and the unification scale are sufficiently high to remain compatible with the experimental constraints regarding the leptoquark induced effects and the proton decay.  



